        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Among the charges was one that Jesus stirred up the people to revolt, both in Galilee and Judaea. The mention of Galilee offered to Pilate a chance of escaping the responsibility of the trial, and led to his sending Christ to Herod, as St. Luke relates (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 23:6-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It was on the return from Herod that the final scene took place. Pilate evidently did not believe that this dignified, meek, inoffensive Man was guilty of sedition, and he desired to hear his defence, which he was willing to receive favourably (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Matthew 27:13",
        "children": []
      }
